            "publisher": "Journal of the International Phonetic Association, 23(2)",
            "url": "https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-the-international-phonetic-association/article/french/E2BC8B1DD975FE4B272B088B8345B933",
            "pages": "73-76",
            "notes": "Documents the ɛ̃/œ̃ merger in Parisian speech (speakers use only /ɛ̃/, especially in northern France) and the loi de position (close-mid e/ø/o in open syllables, open-mid ɛ/œ/ɔ in closed syllables)."
        },
        {
            "id": "tranel1995",
            "author": "Tranel, B.",
            "year": 1995,
            "title": "French liaison and elision revisited: A unified account within Optimality Theory",
            "publisher": "Rutgers Optimality Archive (ROA-15)",
            "url": "https://roa.rutgers.edu/files/15-0594/15-0594-TRANEL-0-0.PDF",
            "pages": null,
            "notes": "Formalises liaison (silent word-final consonant surfaces before a vowel-initial word, e.g. les amis [lezami]) and elision (word-final vowel deleted before a vowel-initial word, e.g. l'ami) as ONSET-driven; establishes that h-aspiré words (hibou) block both liaison and elision despite being phonetically vowel-initial (les hiboux *[lezibu], le hibou *[libu])."
        }
